00:15.320 --> 00:27.040
James Clayton's Lecture The James Clayton Lecture is a special lecture. There
are a series of lectures which are endowed under the will of the late James

00:27.040 --> 00:42.740
Clayton of Torquay, who is an active member of this institution from 1901 to
1944, and to whose generosity we're greatly indebted. The foundation enables

00:42.740 --> 00:53.400
institution council to invite distinguished engineers or scientists to present a
lecture on any subject of importance to the engineering profession at an

00:53.400 --> 01:08.500
occasion such as this. I have very great pleasure in introducing Mr. Gerald D.
Griffin, our lecturer tonight, who took up the post of director of the NASA

01:08.500 --> 01:22.060
Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas, just about a year ago. He was
born in Athens, Texas, on the Christmas day, 1934, and received a bachelor's

01:22.060 --> 01:33.960
degree in aeronautical engineering from the Texas University's Agricultural and
Mechanical College, and that was 1956. He served four years as an officer in the

01:33.960 --> 01:47.000
U.S. Air Force. Now, after this service, he was an aerospace engineer with
Douglas Aircraft, Lockheed Missile and Space Company, and General Dynamics. Mr.

01:47.100 --> 01:59.380
Griffin first joined NASA in 1964 and he joined it at the Johnson Space Center
at that time it was the Manned Spacecraft Center and he was a flight director on

01:59.380 --> 02:14.380
all of the 11 Apollo missions he was lead flight director on Apollo 12 on Apollo
15 and Apollo 17 and also involved in all the Gemini flights as a flight

02:14.380 --> 02:29.380
controller. During 1976 to 77, Mr. Griffin was deputy director of the Dryden
Flight Research Center Edwards in California. Following this post, he was

02:29.380 --> 02:41.440
appointed deputy director of the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, And between
July 1980 and June 1981, concurrently served as Associate Administrator for

02:41.440 --> 02:52.600
External Relations in NASA Headquarters at Washington, D.C. Mr. Griffin left
NASA for a year to become Vice President for Systems Engineering and Management

02:52.600 --> 03:06.020
at Scott Science and Technology, Inc. of Lancaster, California. This he did
until taking up his current position with NASA in August 1982. Ladies and

03:06.020 --> 03:14.360
gentlemen, it is my greatest pleasure and honor to ask Mr. Griffin to present
his lecture tonight.

03:21.280 --> 03:33.560
Thank you, Mr. President. It's a great honor to be here. As I toured the
institution this afternoon, I couldn't help but think what had happened within

03:33.560 --> 03:45.800
the confines of this building in the last 137 years or so. And it's a great
privilege just to be able to be here with you and get the feeling of that

03:45.800 --> 03:58.260
community that has meant so much to the world in what has emanated from these
confines. I thank you for your kind of introduction, Mr. President, that every

03:58.260 --> 04:03.540
time I hear that I quite often wonder if the audience might get the impression I
have trouble holding a job.

04:06.400 --> 04:17.900
I've moved around quite a bit, and it's been a great deal of fun. And when I
left NASA in 1981, I thought I'd probably never see it again, and I had been

04:17.900 --> 04:28.540
home barely a year when I was asked to to come back and be the director of the
Johnson Space Center and I could not stop that call. I had to do it and it's

04:28.540 --> 04:39.740
been an extremely interesting two years. We are at a, what I would call a
pivotal point in the American space program. Maybe I should say even the free

04:39.740 --> 04:52.020
world space program, because it truly is an international flavor now. Granted,
we are still in the center of it in the States, but the tentacles are reaching

04:52.020 --> 05:04.580
further and further each day and I am sure that in the next decade, the free
world will join together even more than we ever have before to do so many and

05:04.580 --> 05:16.220
very exciting things in space. I want to talk tonight about the shuttle,
primarily its engineering aspects, I decided that rather than reading my paper

05:16.220 --> 05:28.040
verbatim, that I wanted to expand it to some degree, and I'll do that, I also
will be using some charts that you haven't, if you have a copy of the paper

05:28.040 --> 05:37.460
you're not in there, but I felt it was important to zero in on a couple of areas
that I thought this audience, particularly, might like to hear about. We are in

05:37.460 --> 05:47.880
an infant stage with the Space Shuttle. Despite of what you hear in the press
sometimes, it's going very well. We have flown all of 12 times, and as most of

05:47.880 --> 05:58.940
you, I suspect many of you have been involved in complex programs of one kind or
another, that has not given us all the answers yet that we will need. And a

05:58.940 --> 06:06.940
number of flights will have to be continued before we have all of the
engineering answers and we'll have some problems yet that we will have to face.

06:07.300 --> 06:17.740
But for a system as large and complex as it is, we are quite happy with the
first 12 flights. And I think that in the next year or so, we will close out

06:17.740 --> 06:23.700
most of the nagging, let me call it that, kinds of issues that are still facing
us today.

06:27.860 --> 06:35.900
The presentation is broken into several pieces. I'm going to start with an
overview of the program because I want to make sure that we all begin at the

06:35.900 --> 06:37.140
same starting point.

06:40.500 --> 06:50.800
I use these two slides to try to give you a feel, for those of you that don't
have it, the feel for the size of this vehicle. It is very large. The

06:50.800 --> 07:02.040
dimensions, While I won't read them all, the Orbiter is roughly the size of the
length of a DC-9. It has an aspect ratio or a thickness ratio maybe is a better

07:02.040 --> 07:11.700
term. They're more like a 747, very, very large vehicle. And I've shown it in
isometric form on the right, just to give you a feel for the major pieces. And

07:11.700 --> 07:23.720
they are as follows. The airplane device, we call the orbiter, it rests at
launch on top of a very large external tank and that external tank carries

07:23.720 --> 07:34.340
liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen and strapped onto the side of each, or each
side of the external tank are two very large solid rocket boosters, the largest

07:34.340 --> 07:48.620
we have ever flown in our country. The total weight of this stack at liftoff is
approximately 5.5 million pounds, give or take a few. We produce about 6.5

07:48.620 --> 07:59.080
million pounds of thrust at liftoff, which is a slightly smaller number than we
had in Apollo. The Saturn V generated about 7.5 million pounds to give you a

07:59.080 --> 08:00.100
measure there.

08:03.840 --> 08:15.620
The, perhaps the heart of the system, if one wants to think of it that way, is
the space shuttle orbiter. The orbiter is a very complex avionics machine. Many

08:15.620 --> 08:24.980
people think of it more like an airplane, but let me assure you, and you're
going to see this later on, it is a mechanical engineer's dream. There are more

08:24.980 --> 08:33.640
actuators, cranks, pulleys, structure, just enough to keep any and all of you
very, very happy.

08:36.600 --> 08:46.380
I want to give you a feel for the profile of how the mission has flown before we
get into some of the details. And then if you'll refer to this slide, it kind of

08:46.380 --> 08:56.000
goes around in a sequence. We end up landing back at a runway and going back
into the launch complex. This is a picture back in this phase right at the very

08:56.000 --> 09:06.020
beginning, where we are starting to roll the vehicle to the pad. And in the next
shot you'll see the vehicle on the crawler transporter headed toward the launch

09:06.020 --> 09:16.300
pad. Now this is a very large piece of machinery, the crawler transporter itself
weighs about six million pounds. It's the same crawler transporter that we used

09:16.300 --> 09:28.140
in Apollo, and we've got two of them. They were refurbed. In fact, about the
only thing we did to them was replace the soft goods since Apollo, and it was

09:28.140 --> 09:39.920
directly usable in this use. The Mobile Launcher is the rather square device
that the stack is sitting on. It weighs another eight million pounds. It, in

09:39.920 --> 09:50.200
itself, is like a little factory. It's got quite a lot of plumbing and servicing
for the vehicle in it. And then the orbiter sitting on top of there in the dry

09:50.200 --> 10:00.340
configuration without any propellants and it's another three and a half million
pounds or so. This brings a total, then, as we're progressing to the pad of

10:00.340 --> 10:10.580
about 18 million pounds on the roll. It moves at about a half a mile an hour to
a mile per hour and it's a distance of about three and a half miles. So it's a

10:10.580 --> 10:24.140
pretty much major part of the day to make the trek from the vehicle assembly
building out to the launch pad. The next shot will show you that as it's coming

10:24.140 --> 10:36.740
up onto the pad, you can see in this area here, this is the flame trench. And
this whole mobile launcher is moved up on top of the flame trench and is set

10:36.740 --> 10:47.860
into place on rather large pistols. And then the crawler is removed. It's
hydraulically lowered, and then it backs back down the pad and gets out of the

10:47.860 --> 11:01.780
way. So then the engines are fully exposed to the flame trench. The next shot is
a shot of the vehicle this happens to be STS 1 made at night. And it's a very

11:01.780 --> 11:10.400
pretty sight. It's always lit up very brightly, some of you may have seen some
launches and they usually occur, Here is something roughly like the birth of

11:10.400 --> 11:20.840
babies. It seems late at night or early in the morning. And it's a beautiful
sight. Very dynamic. And I hope some of you can someday, if you haven't seen

11:20.840 --> 11:33.120
one, see it sitting there. There's a very inspiring thing before lift-off. Just
to see that much energy harnessed, sitting there ready to go is a real sight.

11:36.620 --> 11:49.020
Now, the launch phase begins with the ignition of the main engines. There are
three main engines in the rear of the orbiter. They produce about a half million

11:49.020 --> 11:58.940
pounds of thrust each, and each solid rocket produces about two and a half
million pounds of thrust. So we start the main engines about eight seconds prior

11:58.940 --> 12:08.980
to lift-off. and as soon as they are up to thrust and measured correctly then we
send the ignition signal to the solid rocket boosters and once that happens it's

12:08.980 --> 12:13.220
leaving. Even if the hold down bolts don't fire it's gone.

12:16.140 --> 12:24.840
We've not had a we've that's about a triply redundant system to make sure those
bolts fired the vehicle sits on the on the base of the solid rocket boosters and

12:24.840 --> 12:33.840
there's four attach posts on each and as you can imagine we want to make sure it
lets go. So as soon as you'd like the rocket engine, I'm sorry, the solid rocket

12:33.840 --> 12:41.240
engine, you have liftoff. On the left, the only reason I'm not going to repeat
any of those numbers, they're there. But I wanted to show you that was an

12:41.240 --> 12:49.660
artist's rendition of what liftoff should look like. It's a, you'll notice
there's a date up in the upper right hand corner of October 79. And because of

12:49.660 --> 12:57.400
some delays in the shuttle, we had to get people to trust us, as that's what it
would look like. But finally, on the right, you to see the lift off of a real

12:57.400 --> 13:14.620
one, and indeed, it looked very much like we had planned. The early launch phase
is a very dynamic one, and it happens at about 60 seconds after liftoff, we pass

13:14.620 --> 13:23.480
through a very high queue, a high dynamic pressure region. That's about the
roughest part of the ride. the astronauts report at that point that there are

13:23.480 --> 13:33.300
some vibration, some noise, a lot of wind noise even that they can still hear.
And at about two minutes after liftoff, the solid rockets are expended. All of

13:33.300 --> 13:42.840
their propellant is burned. And they are jettisoned away from the external tank.
And at that point, you still have the three main engines producing about a half

13:42.840 --> 13:51.200
million pounds of thrust each and the orbiter sitting on top of this external
tank that's feeding those engines with liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen. Now,

13:51.300 --> 13:59.360
on the left again was an artist's rendition of what that should look like, and
on the right you actually see the solid rocket boosters. They have been

13:59.360 --> 14:07.660
separated. You can see the three main engines are still burning, and you can see
the faint haze of the external tank. This was taken with a ground-based camera

14:07.660 --> 14:17.300
at Patrick Air Force Base, and then you can see the solid rockets have been
jettisoned and they are still burning some residual, what we call, tail-off

14:17.300 --> 14:27.380
types of propellant, but they're producing a little to no thrust and at this
point, when they go through about 50% of thrust, we immediately get off of it

14:27.380 --> 14:42.740
because it starts to be more of a drag than it is a help, and thrust decays very
quickly. The next shot is a picture of the boosters tumbling before they are

14:42.740 --> 14:53.980
recovered, and in the next shot you will see the deployment of the Drogue
parachute. Here's the drogue that is starting to stabilize this one rocket, this

14:53.980 --> 15:05.700
drogue chute is 54 feet in diameter, and it pulls out three main chutes for each
rocket that are 115 feet in diameter each. So that, these are the largest

15:05.700 --> 15:15.100
parachutes that have ever been built for any operational purpose. And if that
isn't enough on the last flight, we were getting a little water damage in this

15:15.100 --> 15:25.540
half in quite a lot of water damage, because even with 115-foot chutes, we were
impacting the water at about 88 feet per second, roughly 60 miles an hour. So we

15:25.540 --> 15:37.940
wanted to slow that down some more. The last flight, on the right-hand booster,
we flew three main parachutes of 136 feet diameter on each, and we got much

15:37.940 --> 15:47.700
reduced velocity at impact, a lot less damage, and so from the subsequent
flights from here on we're going to fly 136 foot parachutes as the main chutes

15:47.700 --> 16:03.300
the these things land about 122 miles or so down-range and float and are
recovered they float in a vertical mode we go in with the with a nozzle in the

16:03.300 --> 16:12.980
bottom make an airtight seal blow the air blow the water out replace it with air
and they float horizontal at that point and and we tow them into Cape Canaveral,

16:13.300 --> 16:26.620
take them apart, send them back to the factory and get a new one. It comes apart
in several segments. And they are loaded up at Thiokol in the state of Utah. The

16:26.620 --> 16:35.980
segments are sent by rail and then they're sent back to us loaded by rail. As we
go on higher during the launch phase, we finally get to the point where we shut

16:35.980 --> 16:44.980
the main engines off. that's just short of orbital velocity. The reason we do
that is because we want this external tank, which is only piece of the system

16:44.980 --> 16:56.440
that's not reusable, we want it to re-enter the atmosphere, and indeed from the
cap, it does re-enter and go into the Indian Ocean, mostly in very small pieces.

16:57.300 --> 17:05.840
In fact, there's very little of it left. It's a very lightweight structure, only
weighs 78,000 pounds empty. As you can see, it's very large, 28 feet in

17:05.840 --> 17:14.540
diameter, and as I recall, about 150 feet long. And we do a small separation
maneuver, which the artist rendition on the left shows, to get away from the

17:14.540 --> 17:25.400
tank, and in the right-hand picture, is the actual picture of an external tank
that was taken from an engineering camera located on the base of the orbiter

17:25.400 --> 17:33.950
vehicle as it's separated. One of the things that you can see is you can see
some, in the actual photograph, you You can see some charring of the rear end

17:33.950 --> 17:46.170
and that's because it gets very hot. This whole tank is covered with what we
call SOFI, Spray on Foam insulation, used for two purposes, one is to, these are

17:46.170 --> 17:57.670
cryogenic fuels and we must keep them as well insulated as we can and it also
gives protection to the exit heating that we get. And at this point, the orbiter

17:57.670 --> 18:11.370
is moving at a speed of about 25,000 feet per second, slightly short of orbital
velocity. And with the orbital maneuvering system that's on the, and I'll show

18:11.370 --> 18:21.410
you a better picture of this later, but it's located in the pod of the vehicle
back here in the back, two 6,000 pound thrusters, we top off the last bit of

18:21.410 --> 18:30.350
velocity needed to get into orbit about 200 feet or two to three hundred feet
more per second. And at that point we're in orbit and ready to go into

18:30.350 --> 18:30.850
operation.

18:33.430 --> 18:43.250
In the next chart I'm going to go back to the sequence chart because I'm going
to be discussing now this orbital operations portion of the flight before I get

18:43.250 --> 18:58.250
to the entry. This picture on the right is a picture of STS-41B, and I'll tell
you a story of why that's got such a funny number. As you know, we had an

18:58.250 --> 19:09.850
occasion on Apollo 13. One day when we were headed to the moon, the oxygen tank
blew up, and it so happened that we launched that vehicle at 13, 13 hours. And

19:09.850 --> 19:17.950
there are a number of people that says we probably should never have another
spaceship with the number 13 attached to it. So we tried to devise a system

19:17.950 --> 19:30.230
that's got everyone thoroughly confused, but we don't have an STS-13. The four,
when I say 41 Bravo, STS-4, that's fiscal year 84, one is a launch from the East

19:30.230 --> 19:39.410
Coast, and B is the second mission in the year. Now, if I haven't got you all
confused by now, something's wrong. This happens to be a shot on orbit taken

19:39.410 --> 19:48.650
from a SPAS spacecraft This was a spacecraft that was inside the payload bay,
deployed, and looked back at the orbiter. It was eventually recaptured and put

19:48.650 --> 19:57.890
back into the payload bay and brought home, would we find that payload again.
Incidentally, it was built by the Germans very inexpensively. And it was a super

19:57.890 --> 20:11.370
payload. It was three-axis stabilized and performed very well. You're looking at
the two. To give you an idea, this housed two satellites that were deployed

20:11.370 --> 20:20.270
before the shot was taken. Those are sun shields that cover them up to protect
them thermally. And in this picture, they've already been deployed. But those

20:20.270 --> 20:30.590
were the two that failed as they were ignited to go on to higher altitude. And I
might add parenthetically that we have now been working for about six months.

20:30.590 --> 20:38.490
This happened in February. We've been working for the last 5-6 months on
techniques to recover those satellites. And the Indonesians that owned one of

20:38.490 --> 20:46.330
them have given us the go ahead. And we think Western Union is going to give us
the go ahead and we're going to fly a mission month after next, November. Where

20:46.330 --> 20:53.130
we will go retrieve those satellites, put them back into the cargo bay and bring
them back to Earth. And return them to their owners.

20:55.930 --> 21:07.830
Um... This was a place where we got some relatively bad press because it always
was attached to us, NASA. I mean, actually it was a commercially developed upper

21:07.830 --> 21:19.990
stage. NASA did not have anything to do with that development. Satellite users
chose to use them for a price and insurance, etc. Those have all been paid off,

21:20.130 --> 21:29.970
and it is a good stage. On the last mission we did fly two more of the...of this
same upper stage, the mission that just landed, and they worked just fine.

21:30.910 --> 21:41.290
Interestingly enough, we think the problem there was with the composite nozzles
that these devices use, and we have...this, the community has figured out a way

21:41.290 --> 21:51.870
to scan those nozzles. In fact, they're using a CAT scan process, much like the
brain scan, that can detect voids in the composite. We think that's That's what

21:51.870 --> 22:03.370
had happened through a process era, there had been voids in that, and so we've
corrected that. The on-orbit operations can involve a great deal of other

22:03.370 --> 22:11.010
things. Let me show you a picture. This is the deployment of one of those
satellites. I can't tell you which one it is. You can see the earth to the left.

22:12.310 --> 22:21.230
It has been ejected by springs, and it is spinning on its way out of the Orbiter
Bay. I know you don't get to see much of this on TV anymore, but on American

22:21.230 --> 22:30.190
television we replay these things after they happened. They normally happen out
of sight of the station and we have to dump it on video tape. So we get to see

22:30.190 --> 22:39.770
these things happen quite well. We saw all three satellites that were launched
on the last vehicle. Other orbital operations involved this is an experience

22:39.770 --> 22:53.090
what we call the LDF, standing for long-duration exposure facility. It's a 20
,000-pound structure that we have put many kinds of materials and

22:53.090 --> 22:56.450
components—some

22:56.450 --> 23:07.050
electronic components, even—on the outer skin of it. We deployed it about 6
months ago. It will stay in orbit for a year. And then we will go retrieve it,

23:07.430 --> 23:17.090
bring it back down in order to conduct studies on what the space environment
does to these kinds of materials, long duration exposure. Obviously, if we're

23:17.090 --> 23:24.910
going to be, if we want our systems to last longer we're going to have to make
sure that we provide the right kind of coatings, right kind of protection. And

23:24.910 --> 23:35.530
we want to know more about the long-term effects of the space environment. This
was incidentally built all in-house at NASA. Some structures engineers at

23:35.530 --> 23:45.510
Langley Center had a, a real good time at this one. And that's the remote
manipulator arm that you see poking out the top. It's actually holding onto it

23:45.510 --> 23:56.810
at deployment, and then it just let it go. And it's stabilized by gravity
gradient. And with this long axis pointing it to Earth. Another kind of

23:56.810 --> 24:07.430
operation we do is are manned operations. A number of EVAs are scheduled,
extravehicular activities are scheduled in the near future. This is a picture of

24:07.430 --> 24:17.430
Bruce McCanliss on the checkout of the man maneuvering unit. It was the first
time we had put a man outside and cut him loose without any tethers. It worked

24:17.430 --> 24:26.490
very well, and we are in the process now. We've flown another mission since
then. It's when we repaired the SolarMax mission. We did have some problem with

24:26.490 --> 24:35.650
the recovery device. So as a result, we finally captured the SolarMax satellite
that we repaired with the remote manipulator arm. But maneuvering unit worked

24:35.650 --> 24:48.490
fine. We are going to... on the retrieval mission that I mentioned earlier, we
will be using the MMU to retrieve the two satellites that have failed to get

24:48.490 --> 24:57.550
into the proper orbit. And the astronaut will have a device on the front of him,
we call it a stinger, which will actually... he'll fly out and poke it into the

24:57.550 --> 25:08.550
nozzle of the spent stage on the uh on the uh upper stage and then it has a we
call it a molly bolt or a lag bolt kind of device that pulls out then he

25:08.550 --> 25:16.490
tightens it down and he drags it back to the shuttle at that point he puts a
grapple fixture on it remote arm reaches in gets it puts it back into the

25:16.490 --> 25:20.310
payload bay that's what it says here and that's what we're gonna try to do

25:24.090 --> 25:34.270
A fellow that is going to do that is a good friend of some other people here in
the hall tonight. His name is Joe Allen. He is a scientist. He is also one of

25:34.270 --> 25:38.950
the best EVA specialists that we have. Joe got that assignment. He's happy to do
it.

25:43.230 --> 25:52.010
All right, now I'm coming down the right-hand side of the left chart. As we
start to end the mission, then what we do is we slow the vehicle down by about

25:52.010 --> 26:02.190
300 feet per second, and that's enough to knock it out of orbit. We do that with
those same engines that we topped off the orbital velocity with. We just turn

26:02.190 --> 26:03.670
the vehicle around and fire it backwards.

26:06.550 --> 26:15.370
We do that about 4,400 nautical miles from the landing site. At that time, we're
back to about 25,000 feet per second. And in the early stages of entry, as you

26:15.370 --> 26:27.690
see depicted by this picture, the angle of attack is like 40 degrees. So it's
very high. Here is a picture taken again from a ground-based camera during

26:27.690 --> 26:38.810
entry. And this is at an altitude of only about 100,000 feet. And at this point,
the vehicle has slowed down. It is a glider, it has no power, obviously. So it's

26:38.810 --> 26:55.690
a one-shot landing and it better be right the first time. The uh touchdown speed
varies uh to... from about 180 to 230 knots. There is a very steep descent. It's

26:55.690 --> 27:04.950
a 24 degree glide slope. Standard aircraft is roughly on the order of a degree
and a half two degrees. This is very steep. There's a pre-flare maneuver at

27:04.950 --> 27:15.510
about 2,500 feet and then he slows down and crosses the boundary and puts it on
the ground. That has worked very well, and what I want to do now is show you a

27:15.510 --> 27:25.730
little bit about how the structure is put together in the vehicle. Here's a
touchdown on the lakebed. We go to the lakebed on occasions when we did for all

27:25.730 --> 27:35.350
of the landing tests that we did early in the program, because there's a lot of
room for air. It turns out we didn't need much runway and it all worked well. We

27:35.350 --> 27:43.570
also go to the lakebed for the first flight of any new orbiter, and that's one
reason That's why we landed Discovery on this last flight. We landed back at the

27:43.570 --> 27:53.690
lake bed because it was the first time we had flown that vehicle. And we've got,
I should say, we've got three vehicles delivered now, Challenger, Columbia and

27:53.690 --> 28:06.750
Discovery. And we are awaiting the delivery in about March of next year of
Atlantis, which will give us four orbiters. and then there is a... I guess I

