51:59.890 --> 52:08.510
think of, and this I'll have to orient you a little bit, you're looking at the
launch pad, and you'll remember that I told you that as we put this mobile

52:08.510 --> 52:17.870
launcher down, these are the flame trenches. This is where the solid rocket
boosters exhaust their gases down into the flame trench. And on STS-1, when we

52:17.870 --> 52:28.930
flew it the first time, we got a tremendous resurgence of energy from when the
SRBs ignited to the point that it popped and buckled the aft heat shield around

52:28.930 --> 52:42.550
the main engines. The engine's bells were all knocked around and so forth. And
we had to extrapolate from a 1-6 scale model. And we missed it by a lot. So what

52:42.550 --> 52:53.930
we did, and it was obvious, the pictures of the lift off of STS-1, the detailed
engineering were frightening because you can see the engine bells deformed and

52:53.930 --> 53:04.130
you can see the aft heat shield pop a couple of times. So a very simple
solution. This was laid to some folks at Johnson and the Kennedy Space Center.

53:04.570 --> 53:15.210
This is a close up. You can see it not too well here. This is before we put this
device in. But here, these are water troughs. Let me go to the next slide and

53:15.210 --> 53:25.730
I'll show you. this is parachute type material. And that's water you see in
there, about a foot deep, that we just laid across the hole. And the purpose is

53:25.730 --> 53:35.970
that when the SRBs ignite, you absorb that energy with this water. It just blows
this stuff completely away. It's gone. Almost vaporizes it. But it was a very

53:35.970 --> 53:44.890
simple fix. We wrestled with all kinds of ways to absorb that energy so that it
would not go all the way down to the bottom of the flame trench and rebound into

53:44.890 --> 53:56.010
the, into the orbiter. As it turns out, this has worked very nicely. I was
strictly skeptical of this. I didn't think it would work at all, but the

53:56.010 --> 54:02.990
engineers kept running the figures and they said, yeah, yeah it will work. So
sure enough, we tried it, and it has. Now we've got some very exotic ways to fix

54:02.990 --> 54:10.970
it later with water sprays and all that sort of thing, but this thing works so
well and it's so inexpensive, I suspect we'll be stuck with this for a long time

54:10.970 --> 54:21.170
and it's very reliable. But again it's a problem that you wouldn't even think
about. There's no way, as most of you have been involved in trying to scale

54:21.170 --> 54:29.570
large things, When you try to scale them down or when you take something small
and scale it up, scaling errors can really get to you. And that's what really

54:29.570 --> 54:30.090
happened here.

54:33.010 --> 54:44.270
Ok, here was a problem we had on STS-3 and STS-4. Third and fourth flight of the
shuttle. So we tried to close the payload bay doors, and lo and behold, the

54:44.270 --> 54:54.550
first time they tried it, there was an interference, and it didn't work. As a
matter of fact, the latches on that aft bulkhead, which is this area right in

54:54.550 --> 55:03.370
here, would not make up. The door was not down far enough to make up. The
fellows looked at it profoundly and said, Now what have we done to this vehicle?

55:03.370 --> 55:15.710
Well, we had some reasons to be in a tail sun attitude, tail licking at the sun
for a long, long period. And then we also had a reason to be no sun attitude.

55:16.290 --> 55:24.810
And what had happened is the vehicle had gotten very cold on the top, and it
actually made the orbiter, if I can exaggerate a bit, shaped a little bit like a

55:24.810 --> 55:35.810
banana, like this. The same thing happened on STS 4, due to another factor, and
I'll show you why in a minute. But all we had to do was, we just rotated the

55:35.810 --> 55:45.590
vehicle and exposed it to the sun for about four hours, and the vehicle
straightened back out, and then we could get the doors closed. Uh, since then,

55:45.750 --> 55:54.630
we are very careful to ensure that we do the proper thermal conditioning prior
